This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant's Motion to Suppress Evidence, filed.

Defendant Brandon Dixon in court.  Attorney James Edgar Toran in court for Brandon Dixon.  Prosecuting attorney Patrick T. Franken for Amy Spanczak in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Police Officer McKinley appears in Court. 

Case in Court for Motion hearing.  Defense has not filed a proper motion therefore the Court is unable to proceed with a motion hearing today. Court sets 10/31/2022 deadline for Defense to file its motion.  If Defense does not timely file its motion as ordered, the Defense waives its right to pursue any suppression motions.  Case adjourned to Br. 9.
Motion hearing scheduled for November 23, 2022 at 11:00 am.

Defendant Brandon Dixon in court with attorney James Edgar Toran.  Amy E Spanczak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Case in court for Arraignment. Original Information filed.  Copy given to defense counsel who waived reading.  Defendant pled not guilty.

Court schedules next court date for a Motion Hearing and sets 9/12/2022 for the deadine for Defense to file its motion and 10/10/2022 for the deadline for State to file its response.
Case adjourned to Br. 9.  Motion hearing scheduled for October 20, 2022 at 11:00 am.

Defendant Brandon Dixon in court with Attorney James Edgar Toran; both appear by video.  Edward OBrien appeared in person for the State of Wisconsin.  
Preliminary hearing proceeded.  Sworn for the State: MPD Officer J. Kranz. State rests.  Defense rests.  Defense motion to dismiss argued and denied. Court found probable cause and bound defendant over for trial.  Original information received and filed. Defense requests an arraignment date.
*Pursuant to Chief Judge Directive 22-04, parties are hereby notified that effective 7/30/22, this case is assigned to branch 9, Judge Paul Van Grunsven in room 632 of the Courthouse.  Arraignment scheduled for August 11, 2022 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Brandon Dixon in court with attorney James Edgar Toran.  Adam Joseph Best appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Case in court for a Preliminary Hearing. State's witness is unavailable. State requests an adjournment. Defense objects. Court denies defense's motion and ordered case adjourned for for CAUSE a Preliminary Hearing in Preliminary Hearing Court, Room 146 of the Criminal Justice Facility.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for July 21, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

Court ordered the remaining cash bail to be returned to the remitter.
Court ordered no possession or use of controlled substances without a valid prescription and no dangerous weapons or firearms.

Signed and filed, No Contact Order.  Defendant to have no contact with the 1800 block of N. 12th Street, Milwaukee WI.
Court advised defendant that failure to comply with conditions of bail may result in an additional charge of bail jumping.

Defendant Brandon Dixon in court with attorney Heather L. Johnson appeared as friend of the court.  Stephan Eduard Nolten appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Defendant is advised this case is assigned to Judge Stark, Branch 17.
Defendant given a copy of complaint and advised of maximum penalties, right to counsel and right to a preliminary hearing.  Court reviewed complaint and found probable cause to hold defendant for further proceedings.  DEFENDANT DOES NOT QUALIFY FOR PUBLIC DEFENDER REPRESENTATION.  Case is adjourned for preliminary hearing in Branch PE.
  Preliminary hearing scheduled for June 17, 2022 at 01:30 pm.
